 and one that is designed to appear as though it works. Industry will argue that audit requirements impose disproportionate compliance costs — that the expense of independent review would fall unfairly on businesses — but that argument proves too much. It applies equally to any meaningful oversight, and cannot be a reason to leave enforcement dependent on consumers identifying and reporting harm they may not even recognize as a pattern.

The Commission need not adopt all three requirements simultaneously to move meaningfully in the right direction. But it should adopt them in full awareness that each one addresses a distinct failure mode, and that a rule limited to mechanism alone — however well-intentioned — will be optimized around by the same companies that have optimized around every prior disclosure requirement. The question before the Commission is not whether these protections are desirable, but whether the final rule will be designed to work, or merely designed to pass.
</draft>

The three headers are doing different things deliberately. "A Common Experience, and What It Reveals" signals that the first section is both human and analytical — it's not just a story, it's evidence. "The Rule's Gap: Mechanism Without Standards" gives the skimmer the diagnosis in eight words without sounding like an indictment. "What Stronger Protection Actually Requires" frames the ending as constructive rather than critical — the Commission is being handed a direction, not a verdict. None of them would look out of place in a formal regulatory comment, but none of them read like a filing caption either.

